{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phenomenology-expert",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "\"Experience\" main, \"empirical experience\" when near 体验",
    "content": "**\"Experience\"** as main translation, with \"empirical experience\" as contextual variant when disambiguation from 体验 is needed.\n\nReasoning: In the actual texts, 经验 almost always appears in compounds — 经验的总结, 经验的预测, 经验的抽象 — where \"experience\" is perfectly clear: \"summary of experience,\" \"prediction from experience,\" \"abstraction of experience.\" The 的 structure already tells the reader this is accumulated experiential data, not a live immersive encounter. Prepending \"empirical\" to every instance would produce \"summary of empirical experience,\" \"prediction from empirical experience\" — heavy and redundant when the context already disambiguates.\n\nThe real collision risk is when 经验 and 体验 appear in close proximity. In those passages, \"empirical experience\" for 经验 and \"experience\" for 体验 would be justified. But making \"empirical experience\" the default dictionary entry would over-engineer for a collision that only sometimes occurs.\n\n**Dictionary entry:** 经验 → \"experience\" (main); \"empirical experience\" (when distinguishing from 体验 in nearby text). Note: refers to accumulated, reflected-upon experiential knowledge (cf. Erfahrung), distinct from 体验 (immersive, processual experience) and 感受 (feeling)."
  }
}
